            "content": {
                "raw": "For the bulleted list, you'll need to add a hook where yt creates the subparser for the `yt download` command line argument (right [here](https://bitbucket.org/yt_analysis/yt/src/09f0ef297d7068078a021fc8290d9e3519baf82d/yt/utilities/command_line.py?#command_line.py-162)) so that it uses the `RawTextHelpFormatter` from argparse: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3853722/python-argparse-how-to-insert-newline-in-the-help-text.\n\nI'm not sure offhand if doing that will mess with the other help descriptions in an unsavory way, so you might need to add a hack so it only happens for `YTDownloadData`.",
                "html": "<p>For the bulleted list, you'll need to add a hook where yt creates the subparser for the <code>yt download</code> command line argument (right <a href=\"https://bitbucket.org/yt_analysis/yt/src/09f0ef297d7068078a021fc8290d9e3519baf82d/yt/utilities/command_line.py#command_line.py-162\">here</a>) so that it uses the <code>RawTextHelpFormatter</code> from argparse: <a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3853722/python-argparse-how-to-insert-newline-in-the-help-text\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3853722/python-argparse-how-to-insert-newline-in-the-help-text</a>.</p>\n<p>I'm not sure offhand if doing that will mess with the other help descriptions in an unsavory way, so you might need to add a hack so it only happens for <code>YTDownloadData</code>.</p>",
                "markup": "markdown"
            },
